{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Stillness, or the apathy of others\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 By Henry Dale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Stillness: The collective apathy towards the world and one another. Soon the end will come, with the last silent man dying and no one cares.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Bleak sunlight lashes at me as I open my eyes, worn. Crumpled and tear-stained I stumble out of the sofa and make my way towards the fridge.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 My hand reaching into that cold hell. They only find half a pack of salmon mousse, dried out and so very cold but my fingers clutch around it in a cramped movement. Despite what happened, my body refuses to die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I retch at seeing the grey goo but I force down some bites regardless before bending double and crawling towards the bathroom to empty my stomach. The taste of yesterday\u8217's Lon Mei crosses my lips again along with some curses and whimpers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I make my way to the shower and turn it on, the water too hot but I stopped caring.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The mental pain long outlives the physical one these days.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 One by one the drops pound the shower floor in quick succession. For a moment I just sit there to listen, covered in my own filth. I appreciate the wonder of this rare sound for the wealthy have no neighbours to be noisy, I am long forgotten by the world and I don\u8217't care about them. I long to be surrounded by this torrent, block everything out and forget about the world. Forget about her.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I lost her, heart failure said the doctors and nothing I could've done to prevent it. Nothing to prevent the silence to fill my heart, an apathy of living things, a shock till the day I finally wither away myself. My soul dead and body turned to ash in the furnaces of both man and the devil.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 My stream of tears joins the shower\u8217's tears. I want to die but I can\u8217't die, stuck in a cramp of indecisiveness. I turn off that shower, wretched device that hides the pain but doesn\u8217't solve it. Drying myself, brushing my hair and teeth. I could almost fool people to appear human once more, but nothing changes that animal pain of my eyes, those lines of anguish in my face that disfigure it as good as any scar could ever do.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I try to recollect more of yesterday. A bottle of wine lies on the table, still full, I don\u8217't drink, but it\u8217's my suicide bottle. When I\u8217'll kill myself \u8211- finally, you\u8217'd think- I\u8217'll drink that bottle to the bottom. To celebrate the end. Happy end of the world people! I laugh at this thought but the only thing that emerges from my throat is a hoarse sound of terror.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I grab my phone and check the usual websites and chat logs from my childhood, all of them long down. The world turns and you turn along. Or you get crushed like me. The phone deserves to be tossed against the wall, deserves its violent death as I throw it in disdain.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 My aim is off and the phone lands in a couch, will live to see another day. I imagine it to be a struggle of titans, David versus Goliath and obviously the phone is winning.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A bell rings twice, tears through my stream of consciousness. {\i The postman always rings twice.} Usually it\u8217's just trash, commercials and bills, products of an empty system grinding us back to the stardust we once were. And the system is rotten, tarnished by the Stillness, our society\u8217's communal depression. My depression. The world goes on, but in what way? I don\u8217't talk to anyone but myself and hear others do the same.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The mail ends up in the bin along with the rest of my dignity as I drop down in the couch.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The bottle of wine calls out to me, its posh label promising green hills and blue skies. I feel numb as I grab the bottle, uncork it and empty it in my thirsty throat. The alcohol makes my hungry eyes tear. Hungry for justice that no longer exists.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I try to make my way to the balcony in my desire to feel the wind one last time but I slip in a smear of my own vomit. The railing is too close, the fall too deep and I close my eyes to the impending smack on the concrete below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What I expected comes after an endless time, after the torture of seeing my life again. Loving and losing her again.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It\u8217's a bitter end, like the bottom of my wine bottle that smashes down first. I lie on the concrete staring at the ground as my blood and life drains from me into the sewer. People hurry past me, they don\u8217't see and they don\u8217't care.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stillness has claimed one more victim who jumped in his despair. Stillness that makes people not care.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i L\u8217'enfer c\u8217'est les autres.} In both their presence and their absence.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I utter one last word before my end.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Fuck.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u160?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 The Hound of Arnas\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 By Nora\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\cf1 [image: /Users/chapc035/Downloads/writing/fantasy-faction-monthly/ebook-compilation%22images/nora-0.jpg%22]\cf0}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 My ports disengage, returning me to consciousness.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I stay on my back for a while, gaze turned inward, browsing through the nets. While my body warms I review the datafeeds I requested before going to sleep. Soon there is nothing for me to do but roll out of my dingy alcove, one in many in this shabby plug-a-night for cyborgs and droids. No one pays me any mind as I amble through what passes as a lobby and step into the already busy street.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Please, parts!" A hand grabs my coat. "Any parts you can spare, I beg you, for my child, all his ports are outdated, he can't link, ple\u8211-"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The beggar clamps her mouth shut the moment she realises what she is talking to, her dull eyes already hunting for more pliable targets. Smart woman. She will sooner convince an AI to donate parts off its droid body than the likes of me, and she knows it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Shells don't have parts to give. We're bio-engineered integral cyborgs. Expensive models like mine are even grown with full DNA print. Parts tailored for me in a body as perfect as one can dream. If I chopped my right hand and gave it away, no one else could use it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, getting this close to godhood comes with a sixty years binding contract, which is why I'm walking the trash ridden streets of an off-grids slum doing a bloodhound's job. Looking for a human here like a needle in a smelly haystack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The first two days I spent along the dark sea and the beach\u8211-the rocky expense that once held sand, that we still call beach\u8211-where workers on long rafts poled their way through the mass of seaweeds they turn into fuel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I could have been done in half a day, talking to supervisors, or the AIs that regulate our dead ocean's shallows. But unlike its simulations, the sea has a smell and a taste, almost a presence. It fascinated me, so I took my time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Today I walk away from the shore. I've decided to talk to locals or else I'll be here until I catch the carbon plague.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 My legs take me past triage factories, down streets smelling of rancid grease, where mechanics bend over patrons' cybernetic limbs, bartering their services, weaving through cables like jungle creepers, children running past yelling the names of parts they sell; ports, encrypted 9G cards, 5D sticks, or accessory mods.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Soon the street dissolves in a wider field. I scramble partway up a metal gangway that wraps around a building to the roofs. From there I can see, sprawled at my feet, the buzzing activity of the Mud-Market.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Cyborg modders with four arms selling flatbreads faster than they can turn them. People sitting on crates half sunk in the eponymous mud, tearing at steamed bug-buns, furiously betting on some game only them can see. Others haggling over second-hand garments and scraps of food. Even a few ADroids weave through the crowds, projecting bright holos and loud slogans.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I sigh and sit heavily, my legs dangling over the tin roof of a partmonger. This wreathing mass of bodies discourages me, somehow.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Resting my back to the wall, I turn inwards to log into official networks. I find a few agents in the area, and summon the closest, Agt. Edenton, an ID officer.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before long, three kids come running out of the market, out of breath with laugher. I look down. One of them, a little blond fellow, doesn't register to my eyes. Unchipped. Or, more likely, never chipped: someone's illegal brood. Another has a cybernetic arm made of scraps. Both wave at the third, a black haired runt not possibly past seven, who leaves them to enter the street. The gangway quivers under me, heralding the kid's approach.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 He sits not far, flashes his credentials\u8211-this is indeed Edenton\u8211- and opens a private channel for us to discuss away from prying eyes or ears, for all the world just two strangers enjoying the view before them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i 'What's a pricey Shell like you doin' here?'}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I stifle a laugh. The voice that popped in my head is a deep man's bass, completely out of place coming from the scrawny boy. Edenton gives me a withering look, and I sober up as I realise what an ID officer's job would be, shelled as a kid. Hunt unchipped children like the one I'd seen, gain their trust, follow them home, have it tagged, maybe chip them himself. The kind of job you got because someone thought you deserved it...\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I poke his arm, surprised to find him made out of regular flesh.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i 'Is this a BioShell? Aren't those pretty rare and pricey as well? Incubation is hard to do.'}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Edenton's frail shoulders shrug. {\i 'They make kids like me easily, they don't try for perfection. The body decays after a year, so we swap regularly. It's just a pain to be in a tube for two months while a new body grows around you.'}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I'd shiver, if my body could.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To answer Edenton's own question, I display my working seals and credentials, and watch his eyes widen. A military Shell in the direct employ of Arnas CEO, wielding seals that give her unlimited power is a scary sight, I'm sure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i 'This is Halena Tesselandottir,'} I say, flashing pictures of a young woman. {\i 'Used to live in the grids, legal as you please and pretty bigwigged. Took her chip off, came to those slums.'} I wave my hand, letting Edenton imagine the sort of drama that could push someone to such extremes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i 'Back then she was a modder.'} Lists of parts and softwares join the pictures. {\i 'Augmentations, but no cybernetic replacements. I'm pretty sure she downgraded, since many mods are trackable. She was spotted in this slum, so I was sent to find her. I'd like some help.'}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An order dressed as a request that Edenton accepts with good graces. In no time he comes up with a cunning plan that won't damage his cover, and I mentally pat myself on the back for involving him.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We weave our way through narrow streets, continuing our secret dialogue.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I learn that Edenton has been undercover in this slum for four years, and soon guess that he got there by asking too many questions. He's fourty-two, single, grumpy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We spend some time polishing our plot in a back alley. We'll need our public feeds to display some action to look credible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Finally ready, I step into a wider street, Edenton's weightless body cradled in my arms, and stumble towards an older woman, busy smoking in front of a brothel. Edenton's notion being that such Madams know everything, and everyone.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Seima," I call, picking her name from her public feed, "this kid just crashed into me. He banged his head hard..."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Seima rushes up to us with a face like Edenton is her own grandchild. She looks at me with narrowed eyes. Can't blame her for mistrusting a Shell in a muddy coat, but my public feed has a record of the entire "incident" we orchestrated, and Edenton moans, the voice passing his lips a mewling so pitiful that I stare as well. His feed flashes with one of the pictures of Halena I gave him.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "He's been showing that image the whole time, could it be his mother? If you know her, maybe I could leave him to you..."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It's the magical words. Trying to shirk my responsibilities, am I? She'll find the boy's mom in no time, she swears, and furiously propagates Halena's picture through her personal network.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Finding where Halena (or Hena, as she now goes by) works is a matter of minutes. The hardest part of the job is to pry Madam Seima off Edenton.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Out of sight I put him back on his legs, and we hurry to intercept Halena before someone warns her that we've been asking after her.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It's almost too easy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 She's exactly where we were told.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unchipped, so nearly impossible to track, she was betrayed by the simplest of human drives, everyone's inherent need to network and socialise.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Edenton's bass vibrates in my skull. {\i 'What are you gonna do?'}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 He follows me over crumbled walls and up stairwells that lead us to a rooftop. Lying down, we can spy on Halena and her companions, sorting garbage, probably paid by the amount of recyclable they can sift.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I scan her face, still young, but scarred by the mods she took off her temples and neck, as I'd guessed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I extend my arm, fingers splayed, lock, breathe out, and fire.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 My shoulder joint shifts, swallows the recoil. People scream, run to cover. Edenton jumps, grabs me with his little hands. In the street her blood flows, joining the streams of dark fluids down the gutter. Half her head is gone.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u160?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Why," Edenton cries. "What did she do to deserve that?!"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "I never asked," I reply, "and neither should you."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u160?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Everything in Frame\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 By tebakutis\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As the two clean-suited enforcers marched me through from the exit pod into the magnificent bright, I considered my inevitable death. I'd never seen the sun before \u8212- none of us had, other than in videos the director showed on weekends \u8212- and I had never seen anything so bright or beautiful. I couldn't even look at it, not directly, and I longed to feel its heat on my skin. Assuming Gurney was right.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stalks of grass greener than any green I'd ever seen swayed in the gentle wind, rising to my thighs. They brushed against the legs of my clean-suit as they brushed the round, rusted domes of the exit pod. That pod and the long elevator shaft inside it was the only link between Sanctuary Twelve and the surface world.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I took a long look at the world the Overseer had assured me would kill me, the world his oldest and most trusted servant, Gurney Maynard, had assured me would not. I had to act shocked, because this world did not match the dead plains the Overseer showed us so often below. I felt one enforcer push his staff into the small of my back.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Move," the enforcer said.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Or what?" The head part of my clean-suit wouldn't turn to look back at him, but I didn't need to look back to express my disdain. "You'll execute me twice?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A holo screen flashed in front of me. It was a recording of my son, now thirteen and wiry, as he worked beside the others dredging energy fragments out of the deep shafts. The enforcer made it disappear.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The threat was obvious, and I walked without another push from the enforcer's staff. I'd already taken steps to ensure the Overseer could never punish Matty for what I was about to do, but I couldn't let him know that. I had to act like another outspoken problem marching to my inevitable comeuppance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The outside world was poison without a suit \u8212- the sun, the grass, the air \u8212- and questioning that was the only way one escaped the drudgery of the crystal mines. We were safe in the mines, the Overseer assured us. We lived by his grace, his generosity. Everyone outside Sanctuary Twelve was doomed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Soon the enforcers marched me to a clearing, a down swept field of brown stalks crushed beneath dozens of robotic feet, likely less than a day ago. After they poisoned the grass. That streak of death sat in stark contrast to the simple beauty around us. It was a naked, pus-filled scar on a glistening grass plain, but that was the advantage of a narrow camera lens. You could focus on so little and block out so much.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Overseer had constructed a fake exit pod at the top of the descending plain of dead grass, and I recognized that pod and the dead field from the videos I had seen of the others who dared question the Overseer. People who insisted the world above was alive and safe, like me. Murdered people.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The enforcers would force me inside that dome and strip me of my clean-suit, with dire warnings of what would happen if I went outside. When they were ready for me to make my entrance, they would pump the pod full of something noxious \u8211- tear gas? Toxic fumes? \u8211- until my heaving gut and shriveled lungs forced me to stumble out of the front door, into the camera frame.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Then I would die. Then my fellow miners would watch as I shrieked, and burst into flame, and melted. They would watch my seared bones pop, my body brutalized by the poisonous world above.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "The outside world is death," the Overseer would repeat, as those below averted their faces from my melting body. "The claims of Worker 542 are as false as all those before them. Only I protect you."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 They marched me inside the dome, just like Gurney had said they would, and they stripped off my clean-suit, just like Gurney had said they would. All I wore now was my light gray mining jumpsuit, and the air inside the rusting pod was stagnant. I longed to feel the sun on my skin, a cool breeze on my face.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The sun wouldn't melt my skin, and the grass wouldn't melt my jumpsuit, and breathing this wonderful air would not shrink and ruin my lungs. Those horrors would instead be caused by the weapons of the Overseer, hidden out of frame. Microwaves. Heat rays. Infrared. I did not know what those words meant, what Gurney had envisioned when he said them, but I knew they offered invisible death.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I waited until the Overseer's voice echoed through the rusty pod. His voice was pumped up to the surface so the enforcers could hear it, so they could pump in the gas at the proper time. The Overseer was speaking, now, which meant the feed was "live", as Gurney had called it. Time for me to die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I burst out of the front of the rusting pod.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 That was the difference between me and the other victims, you see \u8212- Gurney's betrayal of the Overseer, the clarity provided by a cancer no Overseer medicine could cure, and the death of the Overseer's leverage. Gurney's daughter. Those events conspired to make my death different.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The enforcers had done this a dozen times before. Place the victim in the rusting pod, set up the weapons and the camera, check the camera angle, and then, and only then, pump in the gas. All happened only after the Overseer set the stage, said a few haunting words for this poor deluded fool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 No miner raised as I'd been would voluntarily burst from their safe haven, but I had, before anyone planning to murder me was ready. The outside world felt wonderful. For the first time I felt the gentle heat of the sun on my skin, a cool breeze rushing over my cheeks. Nothing melted. Nothing burned.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 That was the other thing victims of the Overseer couldn't do \u8212- run \u8212- because when your lungs were full of tear gas you made a very slow, very easy target. I was no easy target. I zigzagged down that field of dead grass toward the small, round ball sitting at its end. Toward what I knew was the camera.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I saw the now panicked overseers struggling to set their weapons up, to bring them to bear \u8212- they were mounted, I saw now, on complicated tripods which were still being arranged \u8212- and for a moment, I pondered grabbing a weapon. Yet I was not here to kill anyone, and any overseer was easily replaced. I reached the round black dome as the first overseer grounded his tripod and readied his weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Look at me!" I shouted into the camera. "I'm alive! The world above isn't killing me! They are!"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I struggled to rip the camera from its mount, but it remained stuck tight. I heard a loud hum and then I felt heat that seared my skin and bubbled my eyeballs. The air was so hot I couldn't even scream, yet I didn't die \u8212- not immediately \u8212- and my rage gave me the strength to turn the lens, not up and out of the ground, as I planned, but sideways. Toward the green fields and the enforcers with their weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Even as invisible death set my skin afire I heard the Overseer shouting over the speakers, not to his enforcers, but to those below. His desperate explanations fell on deaf ears. Gurney had whispered to those below as well, and all they needed to start their riot was proof. My death was that proof.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The boiling heat ended at last, perhaps because the enforcer knew better than to waste power, or perhaps because he heard the masses rioting below and knew that running was better than facing those he'd help imprison. None of it made any difference to me. I drank in the feel of that cool breeze.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I wished I could see the sun and touch the grass, stroke my son's face one last time, but I was too busy dying. Had I succeeded? Gurney's crackly voice echoed over the Overseer's intercom\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "We did it!" Gurney shouted, as my people cheered. "You gave us the truth! You gave us the whole world! We're free now, all of us!" The cacophony faded as Gurney faded, as he called for silence.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Thank you," he said, voice trembling over the speakers. "We're coming up. We'll see you soon."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 They wouldn't. No one would reach me in time to save me, but I didn't mind. Matty would grow up breathing this clean air, living beneath this warm sun, sleeping in this soft grass. After decades of slavery, it seemed absurd that our freedom required nothing more than a camera, twisted sideways, but that was the beauty of it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All it took to free us was one traitor. One sacrifice. And one perfect camera angle, everything in frame.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u160?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Border Crossing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 By Jmack\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PFC Charles Walker's final mission was a total fuck-up. Going house-to-house in Raleigh, North Carolina, his squad got separated from the rest of the platoon. Sergeant Morales took a bullet, which left Charles next in rank. They ran, got lost, hid from drones, ran some more. He hardly knew how they got back over the lines.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 His only thought when they stuck a shiny medal on him was how he'd left Morales\u8217's body behind. The sergeant always said "family takes care of family", and in the weird world of war, that was your squad.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Then someone nuked Chicago, and the Second American Civil War was over.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles waited to hear about the sides exchanging their dead, but months went by. The squad said somebody had to get the Sarge, but they were all missing some body part or other. It was just that they knew Charles was going no matter what.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The important thing when going rogue was to swap out your brain chip. You hired a head-hack to pull out the old one and put in a counterfeit, praying he didn't nick an artery or puncture your spinal cord in the process. And if you were hunting someone else's chip--like some dead sergeant's--you needed a tracker box. The squad pooled their savings and still they had to go to the local loan shark to fund the mission.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It only took Charles a few hours to pack his gear, buy a ghost phone, and hitch down to the border. It took three days of waiting in lines, bribing everyone in sight, and praying the head-hack was as good as he claimed, until the guards passed Charles through the gates - just a local guy heading home.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 He hailed an Uber taxi. The driver, tall enough that his head scraped the little car\u8217's roof, was a nice enough guy. But he was smart, too. Didn't believe the chip for a minute and called Charles "Yank" right off the bat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles got out at the nearest hotel, then ducked into a Wal-Mart for a gun. He planned to find the sergeant the next day.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It all turned to shit that night.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A voice over the hotel phones ordered all guests to assemble in the lobby. Charles didn't like it. He grabbed his gear and evac'd down the fire escape. The street was a mess. Cops were forcing people to line up at barricades to be scanned. Charles hung back, listening in on conversations until he pieced together that the Southern government was doing a universal chip reset of its citizens.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "We need to know who's really one of us, don't we?" said a Southern belle who didn't mind at all talking to the handsome black man. "Were you in the Grand Army?"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Yes, Miss,\u8221" Charles lied. He made an excuse and drifted away. People were shouting across the square. Police pulled an old man out of line and threw him into a van.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles needed to move up his timetable, but first he needed a way out of the city. He thought about stealing a car, but that wouldn\u8217't get him past roadblocks. His phone showed an Uber nearby.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Yo, Yank!" said the driver as he pulled up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles snorted. Same tiny car; same too tall guy. \u8220"I need--\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Sorry, friend, but your fake-as-shit chip won\u8217't scan tonight, which means the cops aren\u8217't letting you through."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles slid into the passenger seat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Whoa, hold on --" the driver protested.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "LeRoy, right?"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "It\u8217's Roy. But look - "\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Listen, Roy, I need a favor."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The men stared at each other for a long moment before Roy shrugged and said, "Shit." He pulled out a flat metal box which he plugged into a socket under the dash. "I\u8217'll run your chip on this." Roy explained. "It's a John Doe box. All the best Uber drivers have one. You know, when Mr. Senator This or Miss Socialite That wants to party and no one wants any records left." He pressed a button, and the dashboard displayed a randomized name. \u8220"You know, I usually charge a lot for this kind of favor.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"I can pay,\u8221" said Charles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Not tonight,\u8221" said Roy. \u8220"I don\u8217't like the feel of things tonight.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 They lined up at a roadblock and waited. When it was their turn, a baby-faced cop pointed a flashlight inside to check the number of passengers, read the fake id off the Uber system, and waved them through. Charles sighed, and took his hand off the gun inside his coat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The little car accelerated. \u8220"Where to? The best place for you is back at the border.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Morales had been killed about ten miles southeast. Charles gave the name of the place. Roy sighed. \u8220"You\u8217're just one problem after another, aren\u8217't you? That poor town was shredded.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The short drive took hours, what with cratered roads and bombed out buildings. Roy kept up a monologue about his customers, covering his nerves. "Passengers are like family, right? You don\u8217't get to choose; you just have to do your best by them."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When they got to the spot, Charles fired up the chip tracker.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"You need to tell me what\u8217's going on, Yank,\u8221" said Roy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"My squad,\u8221" Charles began, then cleared his throat. \u8220"My squad got into a hell of a firefight over by that gas station. Lost our sergeant.\u8221" The tracker beeped. \u8220"Morales.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Roy frowned. \u8220"Put your tech away, Yank. I\u8217'll take you where all the bodies are.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 He drove them to a cornfield. \u8220"In there,\u8221" he said.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles pushed through the dry, skeletal stalks, Roy following behind, until they broke through to a clearing the size of a football field, covered over with fresh concrete.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "What's this?" said Charles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Mass grave," said Roy, softly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles\u8217's head pounded. His breath came ragged. He rounded on the Southerner. "You couldn't treat them with respect? You tear the whole country apart, the least you can do is have some respect for the dead!"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Roy's face grew red. "Who're you yelling at? We just wanted to be freed to do things our own way. What's wrong with that?"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 They were in each others' faces, fists balled. \u8220"They treating our people any better up North?\u8221" demanded Roy. Charles didn\u8217't know. He\u8217'd never thought about it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A rooster crowed. They looked away from each other and out to the clearing. \u8220"Maybe your sergeant is near the edge,\u8221" said Roy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Morales wasn't. Her chip pinged thirty yards in. Failure clamped Charles\u8217' heart. He might have sat there forever if Roy hadn\u8217't said they should get moving.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles reached into his pocket and pulled out his medal. It shone in the daybreak as he placed it on the concrete above the sergeant\u8217's grave. It was all he could do for her.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 They drove north. Two miles shy of the border they heard a drone and pulled under some trees. Roy scrolled through the news on his phone. "They've closed all the crossings." He sat and thought. "Look, Lake Gaston gets narrow near the Route 1 bridge. It\u8217's an easy swim. You can swim?"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A red light flashed on the car dashboard. "That's a call-back,\u8221" said Roy. \u8220"All cars back to their registered address."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Let me out here,\u8221" said Charles. \u8220"Roy, they can track you by satellite, by cell tower.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Roy stared out the windshield. "Yeah, well, no one said I can\u8217't take a quick detour on the way back."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The highways weren't safe, but Roy knew the unmapped dirt roads. Ten minutes later, the lake appeared over a rise. They stopped, got out, and gazed at what was left of the United States beyond it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Home of the brave," said Roy. A low buzzing came from the sky to the south, followed by the drone. "You better go.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles handed him his gun. "You might need this."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Against you guys?" asked Roy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Or your own," said Charles. "Fuck if I know." They shook hands. "Take care of yourself."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charles headed to the lake. Glancing back, he saw Roy fold himself into the little car. He walked fast into the cold water.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The drone passed over, banked around in the distance, and started back. He swam. The buzzing passed to his right. A huge blast hammered his ears and shook the water. He glanced back to see pieces of metal flying and smoke pouring from the car. Roy was running away from it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Don't make me come back for you," Charles thought, swimming harder.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The drone circled, coming back his way. Christ, Charles prayed and swam on. The buzz grew louder; it was almost on him.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Gunshots rang out from the shore and the drone veered off. Charles stopped and treaded water. Roy stood at the water's edge, firing into the air and waving his arms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "Dammit, Roy," shouted Charles. "Don't make me come get you!" The drone zoomed across the lake, and Roy fell, then struggled to rise.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The north bank was so close. Charles turned, and swam back south.\par}
