{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"I didn\u8217't do anything!\u8221" I say, sounding the words out loud and clear. Tears stream down my face, a clear indicator of my distress.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The mayor ignores me. He\u8217's heard protest before.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"You are found guilty for the use of black magic. I hereby sentence you to life in the Outlands.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"It was an accident!\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 He slams his wooden mallet on the table. My captors lead me away for the Preparation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"No!\u8221" I scream. \u8220"I\u8217'm innocent!\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The people grow into a tumultuous roar, and by the time I disappear from them, I have cuts and bruises from their sticks and rough fists. My captors don\u8217't seem to care about what they do to me. This is my fate for using black magic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 But it was an accident! Can\u8217't they see that?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 They take me to the Preparation room. No one knows anything about the Preparation. Even the Sending is private. But no one cares except for those in charge and the ones that go through it. I won\u8217't be seeing those throngs of people anymore, I know. I\u8217'm already dead to them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Next thing I know, I\u8217'm stripped naked and my captors leave. The humanoids replace them, modified people, half machine half human, and they carry rods and cables and batons. I don\u8217't know what to make of them at first, but then the reality dawns on me. The humanoids can\u8217't feel like people, though our drugs dull human emotion. They\u8217're permanently unfeeling objects, rid of passions and desires. They make for a pristine utopia here in Dystrandis, but that also means they\u8217're capable of doing things without feeling the results from their actions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 First one strikes, then another. I scream, but the sounds don\u8217't penetrate the room. No one can hear me. Soon, I\u8217'm on the floor in pain, blood staining the cold cement. Then I\u8217'm hoisted to my feet. I stumble alongside them as they lead me to a vault.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Sending, I figure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 They put me inside the hollow tube, naked, bruised and beaten. The glass door shuts. Then up I go, the humanoids disappearing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Up, up, up. My head gets dizzy from the pain of my body and the whirlwind of a ride to the surface.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Outlands. It\u8217's a place talked about in history books at school. They say we burrowed down into the earth when the sun grew too hot. Those were the richest men in the world, the ones with the money to fund projects of preservation. Yet only the purest could remain in Dystrandis. Then came the rules to govern a shining utopia. Rules like the forbidding of magic. If you don\u8217't follow those rules, you\u8217're sent to the Outlands.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The upwards motion stops, the door opens. The heat is stifling and I can barely breathe. A metal rod pokes me in the back, just a tap, but it feels like a sharp needle. I stumble forward, landing weak on a dusty ground. The door behind me shuts and the portal disappears, a metal door preventing me from diving back into the haven of Dystrandis.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I quiver, curling up into a ball. What do I do?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Just then, a call echoes into the shaft. \u8220"Offering!\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I look up to see a group of people coming toward me. They\u8217're clad in dull tones, dirty rags compared to the solid, undeterred colours of the people I\u8217'm used to seeing. Bottles dance at their sides, fastened to their belts. Some carry metal rods, others nothing at all. They gaze down at me with unconcerned eyes. Most prominent are the scars on their faces. Not a face is unmarred.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A man steps forward, their leader. \u8220"A live one, and a beauty,\u8221" he says, squatting to my level.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A woman joins him, her skin as dark as her clothing. She\u8217's a stark contrast to the white world I grew up in. \u8220"She\u8217's weak.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"A worker then,\u8221" says the man.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"She\u8217'll burn,\u8221" says the woman.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Too bad for her.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"But we\u8217've lost so many this year.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Guess that means more water for us.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 He snaps his fingers and two of his band come forward with a blanket. Through weary eyes, I can\u8217't make out whether they\u8217're male or female because of the cloths wrapped around their heads and billowing, ratted robes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Take her,\u8221" the man says, starting off.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I\u8217'm hoisted up and taken out of the shaft. Blinding, burning light stings my eyes and my skin burns after a measly fifteen minutes. I try to speak, to beg for water and shade, but the words won\u8217't form, barely a croak breaking my already cracked, parched lips. Soon, my head grows light. I feel unconsciousness threaten to pull me under, drag me into its welcoming arms away from the heat, the pain, and the sorrow. But a part of me refuses. No, I reason. I cannot give in. Not yet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 So I stay alive enough to notice shade. Then down, down, down we go into the earth. The stifling air gradually cools, a welcome relief for my sweltering body. Eventually, we reach a large cave swarming with people. Hard-working people. They toiled, sifting and scraping at dirty pools, each one\u8217's eyes glazed over as if in a trance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"The workers.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I look beside me and see the woman from before. She retrieves a bottle from her side and pours some water down my throat. It\u8217's not much, but enough to speak.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Where are we?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"The salt mines.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"What\u8217's wrong with them?\u8221" I ask, looking around at the workers. \u8220"They look possessed.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"It\u8217's magic. Let me guess, that\u8217's why you were thrown out? Accused of black magic?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I nod.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Magic thrives here. Some of it can be used for good, but\u8230?\u8221" She motioned to the workers, bent and crooked from a life of servitude.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"I don\u8217't want to become that.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"You don\u8217't, do you? Well, too bad. The boss says\u8217' you\u8217'll be suited as a worker.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I\u8217'm too tired to answer. Instead, I slump my head down, feeling as tranced and bent as the workers we pass by.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"So\u8230?what kind of magic did you wield?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"What?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Your magic. Was it fire? Water? Lightning? Magic is born out of emotion.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"It was fire.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"So you were angry at someone,\u8221" the woman mused. \u8220"Not going to do you much good here. Like I said to the boss, we need water wielders, but it\u8217's a hard one to conjure. Water doesn\u8217't come from sadness. It\u8217'd be a whole lot easier to make if it did.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Where does it come from?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 She looks at me, a thin smile spread across her lips, but her eyes melancholic. \u8220"Joy and laughter.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"But that\u8217's not so hard.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"How do you feel?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I lower my head. \u8220"Terrible.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Exactly.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"But what if I found something to be joyful about?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"This is Utrondis, girl. You\u8217'll find pretty soon there\u8217's nothing to be happy about here.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"I don\u8217't believe you. I\u8217'll find a way to be happy.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 She laughs at me, a mocking guffaw. \u8220"You will, will you? Good luck with that! Even if you recover properly, you\u8217'll still be deformed like the rest of us. And if you\u8217're fitted to be a worker, you won\u8217't be able to feel anything, just like those Dystrandians.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I go to say something, then clamp my mouth shut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 No, I reason. I\u8217'm not about to let this woman be right. Even though I was in despair when I was exiled, I won\u8217't let that defeat me. If fire was built from my rage in Dystrandis, then water will burst from my joy in Utrondis.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Utrondis. A fitting name for the city of the Outlands. I will make it a utopia.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Our kind of Watchman\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 By Peat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I am waiting for the bell to toll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There\u8217's five of us, all with coffee in one hand and a stylus in the other. Stretching out reports and cracking jokes until our shift is done. MacElra is the loudest, the one who aims nearest the knuckle. I worry he\u8217'll get into trouble at his next thought-sensing but today I\u8217'm grateful. He masks my silence. I don\u8217't want them worrying about me. Worry can become questions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The bell rings. I am released.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"I must go quick,\u8221" says young Ronagh. \u8220"Saorne expects me.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Not the only thing she expects, I\u8217'll wager. Hoard your silver, lad.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We laugh at MacElra\u8217's jest, even Ronagh as he flushes. They\u8217're recent news and he\u8217's not comfortable with it yet, but he knows we tease because we\u8217're pleased. Your Watch-brothers are closer than your real brothers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"I\u8217'm for the inn. Any takers?\u8221" MacElra announces.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I shake my head swiftly. \u8220"Not me.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Too many of you have beautiful women,\u8221" he grumbles as I leave.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Outside the Watch-house\u8217's sanctuary, my stomach grows cold and tight like a dead man\u8217's grip. Citizens look at me and move aside. My uniform marks me as a Hierarch\u8217's servant; a figure of law, order, and dread. The Hierarchs know their crimes and I punish them. It keeps Tallabhair whole. I walk home, except I take a turn I normally don\u8217't, knock on someone else\u8217's door.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Come in, Toadstool. You ready?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I nod. I\u8217'm ready to commit my first crime.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There\u8217's three of us. Niaja, heretic mage; polite, withdrawn. Comarach, our patron\u8217's favourite killer; scum.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 And me. The necessary traitor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I take out my key and open the treasury door. The moment I enter, awareness of everything permeates me. I know who is here, what is here, where it is. One of the many blessings the Hierarchs give their Watchmen and right now, the best of them. Niaja\u8217's face is clenched in concentration as she maintains the spell that masks us from my fellow Watchmen. And Comarach follows, ready to kill either of us if we get clever ideas. When I stop, waiting for a man to walk by, he places his blade at my back. I hated him enough before that.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We continue through the labyrinth, ignoring the kings\u8217' ransoms piled to either side. Our patron bade us take the Knife of Riaghaid, and that only. Even if Comarach was not here, I could not afford to anger her.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I have never seen the Knife of Riaghaid before but one thought summons the image. An ordinary thing, dull and notched. The desires of mages are strange. I lead us to it like a bird seeking summer. There are few of my fellows this far in. I take it and the power of it makes my teeth rattle.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It\u8217's all too easy. No one thought to protect it from a Watchman. Our loyalty is legend.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I smile as we walk out. Disloyalty never felt so good.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Tallabhair is riotous at night, the citizens drinking their sorrow. I smell danger in the mead fumes. All Watchmen know the stories and I\u8217'm not protected by my uniform now. It\u8217's the first time I\u8217've been out without my uniform since I was a boy. The thought troubles me more than any threat. A stranger walks in my body, past the crimes I swore to punish. Poppy smokers, unlicensed poets, adulterers. They don\u8217't seem so terrible tonight.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I had no choice, though. I have my own Saorne; Muadha, whose eyes make the Moon Maiden weep and own my soul. Muadha, whose eyes fail more every day, the magical energies of Tallabhair eroding her brain. The doctors told me it was not uncommon, a side-effect of the sheer scale of the Hierarchs\u8217' workings to keep back the hungry sea. They had a cure; the Hierarchs could hardly do their work without one. An expensive one though, they warned me. I paid that no mind. I was a Watchman.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Then the Hierarchs denied me.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I didn\u8217't dwell on it. I was trained to quick action and stoic courage. Instead, I started looking for others who might provide me what I needed for my beloved Muadha, heedless of price. The refusal continued to fester away though. Eating away at the man I was.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We turn a corner and I find myself eye to eye with MacElra. Fear consumes me. Is he waiting for me? Does he know? No, he\u8217's with a woman. His eyes are wide in question.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I open my mouth and Comarach slits his throat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Fucking toadstool,\u8221" he hisses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 My fists ball up. He smirks at me. My hand is on my knife hilt when Niaja coughs. I look and she gestures at the woman. We all realise the truth that the heretic is saying in the same moment; the witness cannot live. She runs and Comarach chases but I am faster. My blade flies straight between her shoulders. I pull it out, the coffee rising up my throat. She\u8217's dead. At least I don\u8217't have to finish her. I don\u8217't sheath it but turn to face Comarach again. His own weapon, wet with MacElra\u8217's blood, is waiting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Perhaps it would be best to settle this matter elsewhere?\u8221" says Niaja. \u8220"Such as, say, somewhere that is not a murder scene.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 She\u8217's right. I clean my knife and sheath it. He takes the lead, unafraid of me. Scum. I glance at Niaja and her lips twitch, then she\u8217's like a statue. We go to the meeting place as quickly as is sensible. As we enter, I nudge Comarach.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"I\u8217'll get you for this.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"No you won\u8217't.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 He\u8217's right. I won\u8217't even remember it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The patron gives me two vials. The first is for Muadha.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The second is for me.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There is a problem with committing crime when your mind is read regularly. The only way to escape capture is to never remember doing the crime. The second vial will solve that problem. But there is more, as my patron had explained when we first made our bargain. The Hierarchs are not fools. If a man receives a great prize but cannot remember why, they will prod and probe until they have the truth. And what greater prize is there than the miraculous recovery of your wife from the surest disease in Tallabhair?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When I wake tomorrow, Muadha will be well, but not with me. She will be somewhere else and I will believe that the strange corpse lying next to me is hers. Every little drop of pain I\u8217'd thought to escape will be mine, right down to the dregs. When my patron told me, I nearly begged her to find another way. To make me vanish too so that we could be together. I know she has a use for men such as me, if a man like me was willing to be scum.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I was not brave enough.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Now the vials are in front of me and I want to ask her for this mercy. I\u8217'm still not brave enough. I tell myself it is necessary. No one will suspect a thing if Muadha dies, but if we both disappear after tonight, people will come looking. People like Comarach.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is three weeks since the night that both MacElra and Muadha died. I sit away from the others as I write my report, my coffee laced to keep me numb. My Watch-brothers watch me quietly. They wish to heal me but don\u8217't know how. They don\u8217't know how to heal themselves. MacElra was our soul. We take our pain out on the scum who did it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 My mind wanders constantly. I keep starting to write a resignation rather than my report. My captain, MacCuoma, refuses to consider such a thing. He tells me it would dishonour their memories. Maybe he\u8217's right; I struggle to know. I am grateful for his care, for my brothers\u8217' sympathy. It\u8217's MacCuoma who tells me when the bell rings, tells me to go home. He emphasises the word home. Citizens look at me with fear and pity. I\u8217'm not just a Watchman to them, I\u8217'm a human too.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I reach my empty dwelling and look for the mead bottle. It\u8217's not where I left it but there\u8217's a small one in it\u8217's place, it\u8217's contents a pale yellow. Like amber. Or piss. I don\u8217't care, I drink it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As I do, I notice the woman. She wears no marks of belonging and a deep hood that doesn\u8217't quite conceal the inhuman perfection of her face. I finish the vial, my mind sluggishly accepting the impossible reality.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Hello, Watchman. We still have business, you and me.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 She is right. I try to open my mouth, to ask after Muadha. When I can be with her. I can\u8217't, but she smiles anyway.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"There is a man,\u8221" she continues, \u8220"Who has offended me. He believes himself safe.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I understand her request. All of it. I nod, heedless of price.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Little by little, we slipped into the dark\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 By OnlyOneHighlander\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"It was the best of times, it was the worst of times, it was time for a Pepsi\u8230?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Much better, thought Milton, returning {\i \u8216'Pepsico presents A Tale of Two Cities\u8217'} to the shelf. His hand lingered on the spine of the book as he let his gaze wander across the other titles: {\i \u8216'The Famished Road brought to you by Mars\u8217'}, {\i \u8216'The Grapes of Wrath in association with Jacob\u8217's Creek\u8217'}, {\i \u8216'The Odyssey: Ryanair edition\u8217'}. It had worked. He knew it would.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before the last election, the country\u8217's libraries were on their last legs. No budget to maintain them, and who would agree to more taxes so someone else\u8217's children can read books. No-one, that\u8217's who. A knotty problem, but one that had been solved many times before. It just took a man with the right amount of imagination and, despite what his Year Seven report card might have said, he had it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A knock at the library door. Stephanie, his chief aide, popped her head round the gap. \u8220"Two minutes, sir.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Thank you, Stephanie,\u8221" he said. Stephanie wasn\u8217't her real name of course. Or at least it hadn\u8217't always been. Employability data shows, she had explained to him, that her original name was likely to hold back her career, so she changed it. It had cost her, and had mother had been none too pleased, but, given her current position, it was clear to see it had been a wise investment. And of course, she had not repeated her parents\u8217' mistake with her own children.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It was right, Milton said to himself, to hold the speech here, his old stomping ground. This school had given him so much, now it was his turn to give back. He took a final sip of his cappuccino, dropped the green and white cup into the recycling bin, straightened his tie and took hold of the door handle.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 *\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Children,\u8221" Milton paused to look across the crowd, \u8220"Children are our most important resource. They are the workers of tomorrow, the life blood of our economy, they are - ladies and gentlemen - our future.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Ensuring this future, securing the best chance of success for our children is, surely, the most important function of a government. And I can assure you, my government sees the unlocking of our children\u8217's potential, preparing them for the global marketplace - with all its risks and uncertainties - as our most sacred duty. However, the question must be asked, is government, is the state with all its inefficiencies, its bureaucracy, best placed to carrying out this function?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Can we expect our hard working teachers,\u8221" Milton let his eyes flash to the front row, the faculty row, where the wise old farts had squatted at so many assemblies, \u8220"Can we expect them to know which skills young people will need when they enter our ever more competitive economy? Can we expect our civil servants, shut away in Whitehall\u8217's ivory towers, to be able to predict where we will be, what the key industries will be ten, fifteen years into the future? I remember, growing up, we were taught \u8216'you must learn your times tables, because you won\u8217't have a calculator in your pocket wherever you go\u8217'.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Milton took his smartphone from his inside pocket and held it up for all to see. \u8220"And that was right, of course,\u8221" he continued, the audience\u8217's chuckles proof his speechwriter\u8217's concerns over this play to the gallery were unfounded. \u8220"Because instead we have supercomputers!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"And we have this magical machines all thanks to the dynamism, the creativity and drive of the free market.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Now, we all know the market is not perfect, there are always winners and losers, but it has been proven - time and time again - to be the best tool for organising resources and improving the common lot of humanity. And I believe it is time to bring this, our best tool, to bare on our most important function.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Liberalisation of investment into and delivery of education will bring this dynamism, this creativity to where it can do the greatest good. Under the reforms published today, companies and international corporations will now have the ability to set up their own schools, with children free to choose their own futures.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Rather than learn coding and computer science from a teacher - who may have finished studying five, ten years ago - wouldn\u8217't it be better to learn these skills from Google or Microsoft? Rather than learn about mathematics from old Mr Brickland - who told me about those calculators - wouldn\u8217't it be better to learn it from Barclays or Pricewaterhouse Coopers? It is the difference between being taught about Shakespeare and being taught by Shakespeare.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"And if one of these talented young people,\u8221" Milton cast a hand across the youngsters sitting on the stage beside him. Stephanie had been right. Having the school\u8217's current pupils in the hall would make for a great photo opp after the speech. \u8220"If one of them excels at their new studies, and is ready to enter the workplace and earn a wage, should we shackle them to an arbitrary age limit? If a person is fifteen, fourteen, twelve, and wants to take a job, and has the necessary skills, should this aspiration not be applauded? After all, we don\u8217't stop people from working because they are too old anymore. Why should we deny people the right to work because they are too young? To do so is a patronising assault on liberty, on the freedom to choose, and I am here to tell you today, we will put up with it no longer!\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The thump of MIlton\u8217's fist on the lectern echoed through the cavernous assembly hall. He looked up. His fingers in his free hand were shaking. A long, slow breath eased from his lungs\u8230?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 And then the applause began.\par}
